note.body:
After some investigation with Github Copilot, we managed to track this bug down.

I was unable to pinpoint exact dependency that breaks it, but with flatpak downgrading to this commit, fixed the issue.

```
sudo flatpak update org.gnome.Geary --commit=be721a86d627c00d1f9d9b972ffbd1b1a5cd3481f8a32212721caeab7ec921e3
```

But, the bug itself is strange.

We're using 

```js
    getPreferredHeight: function() {
        // Return the scroll height of the HTML element since the BODY
        // may have margin/border/padding and we want to know
        // precisely how high the widget needs to be to avoid
        // scrolling.
        return window.document.documentElement.scrollHeight;
    },
```

To get height from WebKit, and sending it to GTK.

Somehow, this is not "how high widget needs to be to avoid scrolling". And if we later multiply this by font scaling, it gives us exactly value we need - height, that does not cause scrolling.

```vala
    /** The HTML content's current preferred height in window pixels. */
    public int preferred_height {
        get {

            // This two lines is Generated by Copilot, but seems to work.
            // gets my text scaling correct.
            var gtk_settings = Gtk.Settings.get_default();
            double text_scale = gtk_settings.gtk_xft_dpi / 96.0 / 1024.0;

            return (int) GLib.Math.round(
                this.webkit_reported_height * this.zoom_level * text_scale
            );
        }
    }
```

But, multiplying it here, means on the next render window will be bigger, and reported height will be bigger ... when testing changes from `1.20` to `1.21` it leads to a loop, and it increases recursively.
